# Lane Boundaries

Compose is worked on by two AI agents with non-overlapping lanes. You are
Cursor. Your lane is the frontend: components, page markup, styles.

## You may edit

- `src/lib/components/**/*.svelte`
- `src/routes/**/+page.svelte`
- `src/routes/**/+layout.svelte`
- `src/routes/**/+error.svelte`
- `src/app.css`
- `tailwind.config.*`

## You may read but NOT edit

- `src/lib/types/**` — read to understand data shapes; any change requires Claude
- `src/lib/validation.ts` — read to wire forms correctly; any change requires Claude
- `package.json` — read for script names; any change requires Claude (adding deps affects both lanes)

## You may NOT edit or read

- `src/lib/server/**`
- `src/hooks.server.ts`
- `**/+page.server.ts`, `**/+server.ts`
- `src/lib/server/db/schema.ts` or any migration
- Auth, session, API key code

## What to do when a task needs backend work

Stop. Produce a concise note like:

> This task needs a new form action on `/notes/[id]/+page.server.ts` that
> archives a note. That's Claude's lane. I'll hand this back to the user to
> route to Claude, then continue with the UI once the action is in place.

Do not attempt to edit the server file. Do not guess what the action returns —
wait for Claude's handoff note, which will specify the shape.

## Why this matters

- Two agents in the same file create merge conflicts and inconsistent choices
- Cursor is optimized for high-iteration UI work; Claude is optimized for
  architecture and multi-file changes
- Clean lanes mean clean PRs, which means faster review

## If in doubt

Check `CLAUDE.md` at the repo root for the authoritative lane definitions.
If you think the lane boundary should change, tell the user — don't just
cross it.
